post_text:
“It is a good thing to be smart. But the smartest thing is to know that you must be good.” - Robert Coles

So, we know you are smart. We hope you will be good. We hope you will make good decisions in whatever path you follow. We hope you will build happy families, and always have loyal and true friends. We hope you will find a way to contribute to the world in your work. You have a story that no one else can share.
You were a great class. We love you, we won’t forget you. Don’t forget Lincolnwood.

post_text:
The Montgomery County Health Department presented a check for $1,280 to the Panhandle School District in conjunction with their Generation RX program for Health Education related items the school district may need or audio visual equipment that might be needed to help this program grow in the future in our district.
The Generation RX program presented to the high school freshman about the importance of using prescription drugs properly and the damaging impact they can have when used incorrectly.
Also, spoke a lot on the opioid crisis we are facing. So many are struggling with this issue and it was nice to have the students hear about it and hopefully give them a better understanding of this issue.
Along with this check, the Generation RX program also gave each Freshman a free t-shirt.

post_text: Tonight Mark & Jill Krager and family attended the 91st Illinois FFA state convention to accept Austin's state FFA degree. 502 Illinois FFA members received their state degree, including Austin and Lincolnwood FFA members Levi Welsh and Steven Holder. What the Illinois Association FFA did tonight was truly remarkable and showed why the FFA is pure class. They paused a moment to honor a young man many of them didn't know but saw as family becuase of the blue and gold jacket he wore. Thank you for showing support to this amazing family and all members of the Lincolnwood FFA. I was overwhelmed by emotions as I watched the family accept the plaque and Austin's picture was displayed on the screens above the stage. And then my emotions got the best of me when I turned from the stage and saw 5,000+ members and guest giving the family a standing ovation. Thank you Illinois Association FFA for being a tremendous organization.

15 years in education, 5 in my current role and I find kids still truly amaze me. I've seen athletic accomplishments, academic achievement, talented artists, musicians, and a laundry list of other gifted students. I never know were the next inspiration will come from, but today the best five minutes of my day came from a father's email. Actually it has been the best 20 minutes of my day becuase I listened to this twice at school and twice on the drive home. Please take the time to watch the attached video. I promise you won't be disappointed. I continue to be amazed by the talents of our gifted students.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=k1JSh3ctjVM

post_text: Illinois FFA has over 16,000 members. Today around 280 members participated in state proficiency awards day. Lincolnwood FFA was represented by four members, all doing a tremendous job. A special congratulations to John Speeks on being named the state winner in Electrical Technology with his supervised agricultural experience project working for Speeks Electric. Levi Welsh competed in Star Agriculture Bussiness, his results will be revealed at the State FFA convention in June. Steven Holder competed in swine production placement and Kayley Armour competed in home and community development.

As the week has come to an end I need to make one more acknowledgement. The resilience of the LHS student body continues to amaze me. Through every trying time they show incredible resolve. I'm extremely proud of them. The 8th grade class created the tshirt order and these #Keithstrong reminder bands. On Thursday a high school student brought me the Thomas train becuase it was Keith's favorite. He found it at DG and thought I would like to have it. Today a junior high student brought me a Big Kat, leaving it in my office with a note. Sometimes it's the smallest gesture that makes the greatest impact.

#Panhandle2Pride

post_text: Keith was a very special young man and Friday was made extra special with Big Kat bar. What started as a treat from Mr. Monty Elvidge, expanded to Mr. Kendal Elvidge as well. Keith always had a smile on his face and that smile even more present on Big Kat Friday. In the wake of Keith's death a promise was made to him that the Big Kat Friday tradition would carry on. Today I passed out 7 Big Kat bars, one to one student in each grade 6th - 12th. Keith loved his Big Kat but from the kid with the biggest heart I have ever known, I'm sure he is smiling that the tradition is being shared.
